Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Kenya Airways, United Bank for Africa

-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 
2011-05-25T16:20:51Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-25/sub-saharan-african-stocks-united-bank-for-africa-dedlines-by-daily-limit.html
The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share
Index retreated for the third day, dropping 0.5 percent to
25,618.53 by the 2:30 p.m. close in Lagos, according to an e-
mailed statement from the exchange.  Kenya’s All-Share Index snapped three days of losses,
advancing less than 0.1 percent to 74.91 by the 3 p.m. close in
Nairobi. Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index rose for the first day in
three, gaining less than 0.1 percent to 2,085.20 by the 1:30
p.m. close in Port Louis. Namibia’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098) 
climbed for the second day, less than 0.1 percent to 841.45 by
the 4 p.m. close in Windhoek. Ghana’s bourse was closed for a
public holiday.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Kenya Airways Ltd. (KNAL)  , sub-Saharan Africa’s third-
biggest airline, jumped 75 cents, or 1.9 percent, to 41
shillings, the highest closing price since Feb. 14, after the
Kenyan government asked  India  to allow the airline to begin
flying to new routes.  United Bank for Africa Plc (UBA)  , Nigeria’s fourth-
largest lender by market value, slumped 32 kobo, or the maximum
daily limit of 5 percent, to 6.08 naira, the biggest drop since
March 31, after the  Central Bank  of Nigeria increased the
monetary policy rate half a percentage point to 8 percent
yesterday and raised the reserve requirement to 4 percent from 2
percent.  Diamond Bank Plc (DIAMONDB)  , retreated 31 kobo, or 5
percent, to 5.92 naira, the lowest since April 14.  Skye Bank Plc (SKYEBANK) 
, fell 15 kobo, or 1.8 percent, to 8.25 naira, the
weakest since May 6.  To contact the reporter on this story:
